did.abstract: The Metropolitan Council on Housing was formed in 1959. Veteran housing activists associated with the left (notably the American Labor Party and the Communist Party) played a prominent role; these included Esther Rand and Jane Benedict, longtime MCH leaders. MCH has fought for increased public housing, the maintenance of rent control, and other housing priorities, using a range of tactics that included rent strikes and lobbying. The records contain subject and administrative files, and include clippings, correspondence, minutes and other internal documents, press releases, reports, printed ephemera, government documents, audiocassettes and videocassettes. NOTE: This collection is housed offsite and advance notice is required for use.

bioghist.head: Historical/Biographical Note
bioghist.p: The Metropolitan Council on Housing was formed in 1959. Veteran housing activists associated with the left, notably the American Labor Party and the Communist Party played a prominent role, including Esther Rand and Jane Benedict, longtime MCH leaders. MCH has fought for increased public housing, the maintenance of rent control, and other housing priorities, using a variety of tactics, including rent strikes and lobbying. MCH is a membership organization, and also has chapters based on buildings. MCH publishes The Tenant/Inquilinoand hosts a radio program on WBAI, "Listen to Housing Notebook." The organization's website is: http://www.metcouncil.net/ (accessed June 18, 2007).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: The records, unprocessed as of this writing, contain subject and administrative files, and include clippings, correspondence, minutes and other internal documents, press releases, reports, printed ephemera, government documents, audiocassettes and videocassettes. They are organized into four series: I. Administrative Files; II. Subject Files; III. 2002 Accesion; IV. 2008 Accession. NOTE: This collection is housed offsite and advance notice is required for use.

Series I. Administrative Files(9 linear ft.), includes executive board minutes, documents relating to MCH's workshops, its annual assemblies and conferences, and to the MCH Community Improvement Fund, files relating to housing code enforcement and fuel cost pass-along, and queries from tenants and tenant groups.

Series II. Subject Files(14 linear ft.), contains files relating to Columbia University and its relations with Morningsiders United, Mitchell-Lama and other public housing, the National Tenants Organization, New York State housing legislation and related lobbying efforts, rent control and rent stabilization, the Unity Party, Tenant Unity Day, urban renewal, and warehousing.

Series III. 2002 Accession(39 linear ft.), contains subject and administrative files relating to the themes covered in Series I and II, and files on Met Council's radio program on WBAI, including audiocassettes of interviews, MCH branch and building organizations and other tenant organizations, including the Cooper Square Committee, East Side Tenants Council, and the Riverside Edgecombe Neighborhood Association, the Neighborhood Preservation Program, squatters, files about Jane Benedict and Esther Rand, and some Spanish language tenant materials.

Series IV. 2008 Accession(8 linear ft.), contains subject and administrative files relating to the themes covered in Series I and II; topics and organizations most prominently represented include the Division of Housing and Community Renewal, rent control and rent stabilization, co-op conversions, and lobbying activity in Albany, New York.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The collection is unprocessed. Series one and two are arranged alphabetically; the folders in series three are in the order in which they were received (no apparent system of arrangement); series four is arranged alphabetically within each box
